<div id="review_2235449057" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2235449057" />
    <a title="Anthony" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/57796270-anthony"><img alt="Anthony" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1493991101p2/57796270.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2235449057?book_show_action=true">Nov 01, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Anthony" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Anthony" href="/user/show/57796270-anthony">Anthony</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Mass Market Paperback 9781417616541" href="/book/show/3358423-witching-hour">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2235449057" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer14385919010600201426">Not bad at all for my first Anne Rice book. So much so, that I&apos;m willing to continue on with the series and see what happened with Lasher after the first story. No spoilers there, since the next book is called Lasher.<br/> A few complaints, which caused a one-star deduction: 1- this was very overwritten for my taste. As much as I love sweeping epics and giant page counts, this sort of style wasn&apos;t quite what I&apos;d have in mind. The material could easily be cut down and still maintain plot, atmosphere, </span>
  <span id="freeText14385919010600201426" style="display:none">Not bad at all for my first Anne Rice book. So much so, that I'm willing to continue on with the series and see what happened with Lasher after the first story. No spoilers there, since the next book is called Lasher.<br /> A few complaints, which caused a one-star deduction: 1- this was very overwritten for my taste. As much as I love sweeping epics and giant page counts, this sort of style wasn't quite what I'd have in mind. The material could easily be cut down and still maintain plot, atmosphere, etc, very well. Anne Rice seems to enjoy dragging things out and over emphasize. Well after I got the point, she'll continue to describe Rowan's passion, or Michael's confusion, or their love for each other. I like details, and a lot of them, just keep it moving though. (I dont mean to sound so negative, as it wasn't THAT bad).<br />2- Too much romance, that it felt a little cheesy in some spots. I guess that's Anne Rice, though. I can look past it. I enjoy a little passion and some good sex scenes, but not all the mushy mushy crying-because-I-love-you-so-much kind of passion. I believe that they fell in love on their second day of meeting each other.<br />3- this was definitely written from a women's perspective. Not something I would deduct stars for, because I get it... a woman wants to write how she sees and feels. But as a male reader, I guess I don't really care about how big and thick his cock was, lol<br /><br /> Okay, those were my complaints, but not a big deal. I thought the story was brilliant, and how it was told. The Talamasca was narrating for a large portion of the middle, and it was a great ride through history. I love creepy European settings, and witch trials, and the scene with Deborah and Lasher was incredible!<br />Then the stories of Julien, Marybeth, and Stella was a lot of fun, the setting being in the deep south at the turn of the 20th century. <br /> And lastly, I enjoyed the ending, even though it took 300 pages, lol! I enjoy seeing how things turn out with Rowan, her meeting Carlotta, and how it all ends with Lasher. That was some grade A horror</span>
  <a data-text-id="14385919010600201426" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


